nd":"Higham, Suffolk, England","Tunstall, Suffolk, England":"Tunstall, Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"1372–1 March 1448":"1372–1 maart 1448","1372–1448":"1372–1448","1368–1409":"1368–1409","1398–1480":"1398–1480","1346–1359":"1346–1359","1348–Female":"1348–Overleden","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1480":"1480","1 March 1448":"1 maart 1448","1448":"1448","1348":"1348","1359":"1359","1346":"1346","1368":"1368","1398":"1398","about 1398":"circa 1398","7 February 1409":"7 februari 1409","1409":"1409","23 May 1398":"23 mei 1398","Higham, Suffolk, England":"Higham, Suffolk, England","Tunstall, Suffolk, England":"Tunstall, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1372–1 March 1448":"1372–1 March 1448","1372–1448":"1372–1448","1368–1409":"1368–1409","1398–1480":"1398–1480","1346–1359":"1346–1359","1348–Female":"1348–Deceased","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1480":"1480","1 March 1448":"1 March 1448","1448":"1448","1348":"1348","1359":"1359","1346":"1346","1368":"1368","1398":"1398","about 1398":"about 1398","7 February 1409":"7 February 1409","1409":"1409","23 May 1398":"23 May 1398","Higham, Suffolk, England":"Higham, Suffolk, England","Tunstall, Suffolk, England":"Tunstall, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hune","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Wessel.","North German: from a short form of   Hubert  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hubert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Armand, Normand, Olivier, Adlore, Alphonse, Andre, Benoit, Camil, Camille, Fernand.","German, Dutch, English, French, Walloon, Breton, Polish, Czech, Slovak, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was borne by an 8th-century Christian saint, bishop of Maastricht, who was adopted as the patron of hunters, and helped to increase the popularity of the personal name, especially in the Low Countries.","History: Jean-François-Barthélemi Hubert from Granville in Manche, France, married Félicité Arsenault in Havre-Aubert, QC, in 1801. Nicolas Hubert <i>dit</i> Lacroix from France married Marguerite Landreau in France <i>c.</i> 1653, died in Montreal, QC, in 1687. René Hubert from Paris, France, married Françoise (de) Lacroix in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. Pierre-Paul Hébert/Hubert from France married Suzanne Laporte in QC <i>c.</i> 1716. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":10,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSumma